Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

Big data transformations are a typically excellent source of bugs and this is certainly true of QEMU, we found a whole bunch of issues with the way QCOW2 and other file formats were handled.

I have no problem with the patch in principle but the way I read this is that the default configuration would be to allow this behaviour, in my opinion this should be turned off by default. Deployers who trust their users (some private clouds) may want to turn this feature on.

Happy to discuss further, not trying to be a seagull here (swoops in, craps on stuff, leaves...) but the SecurityImpact tag brought me here so that's my $0.02

Patch Set 19: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I'm still OK with the semantics of the patch, but it would be really nice if you could address at least the editorial comments. I repeated some of them in my comments.

About the security impact: I agree that some sanity checking would be nice.  Loganathan Parthipan mentioned the case where the (virtual) size of the uploaded image could be ridiculously large, which would lead to a large space reservation when converting using qemu-img convert.  Probably he was thinking about the conversions to RAW from compact formats.  (These conversions happen to interest me as well, because we use RBD, which likes RAW images best, but customers will often want to upload images in some compressed format such as QCOW2.)

If I understand correctly, Glance already has an (optional) quota mechanism; it would be nice if this could be used to protect us against such kinds of abuse.  If not, then I think we need to run "qemu-img info --output=json" and check the results for acceptability, possibly using Glance's existing quota mechanism.
